<br>
The problem isn't that Bush backed out of the agreement, it's that NK backed out (without telling us btw).  I don't think they left Bush any choice really.  It's like if I go up to you and say, I'll give you my car for 10,000 bucks.  You agree, you pay me 10,000 bucks, I pocket the cash,then say I've decided to keep the car too.  However, I'll give you the car if you give me another 10,000 bucks, so you reluctantly agree to give me another 10,000 bucks.  Then I say I've decided to keep the car again, but I agree to sell you the car for another 10,000 bucks.  Eventually, you're going to stop giving me money and demand you get the car.  That's what Bush is doing.<br>
<br>
I agree that preventing NK from getting nukes is of great importance.  Most people are far less concerned about NK using nukes than they are about NK selling nukes to Bin Laden or some other terrorist organization.  MAD doesn't work on some of those people, as they don't mind dying for their cause.  They believe they go to heaven if they die in jihad, which means MAD simply is not a persuasive deterrent.<br>
<br>
I believe that NK decided they were going to pursue nuclear weapons regardless of what the rest of the world did.  They figured they'd lie and make treaties to try and get something out of it, but I don't think there was any real intention of ever not making nukes.<br>
<br>
